title: How bystanders can perform high quality CPR, using the TCPR link
How high quality CPR can drastically increase the chance of survival from cardiac arrest
New Component Title
body: Created by Laerdal Medical 2021

title: The importance of CPR
body:
The odds of surviving from sudden out-of-hospital cardiac arrest is only about 10 percent.

However, if high quality CPR is delivered immidiately after cardiac arrest the chances of survival increases to 45 percent.
 

https://cpr.heart.org/en/resources/cpr-facts-and-stats

title: New Component Title
body:
TCPR Link connects myResponders with the dispatcher in cardiac arrest incident.

By streaming real-time data of the CPR performance from the bystander, the dispatcher is able to provide critical telephone support, to optimize quality of CPR delivered before the ambulance personnel arrives and takes over.

title: A card and an app
displayTitle: A card and an app
body:
TCPR Link is comprised of a CPRcard and TCPR Link app.

The CPRcard is a pocket size card which can measure the rate and depth of your compressions and provide continuous visual feedback. The CPRcard is connected to your smartphone. It should be placed on the chest of the patient to measure the rate and depth of your compressions and provide continuous visual feedback.

TCPR Link app is an app on your phone which provides visual feedback and streams your performance data in real time to the dispatcher, who is a skilled CPR coach that will guide and encourage you to perform quality CPR until the ambulance arrives and takes over.

title: Step 3/8. Turn on CPR Card
displayTitle: Step 3/8. Turn on CPR Card
body:
Pinch the power button to turn on the CPRcard.

It will now automatically connect to your phone through Bluetooth.

title: Step 5/8. Phone placement
displayTitle: Step 5/8. Phone placement
body: Place your phone face-up beside the patient's head and kneel down by the patient's shoulder opposite your phone and prepare to give CPR.

title: Step 7/8. Begin CPR
displayTitle: Step 7/8. Begin CPR
body:
You are now ready to begin giving chest compressions.

You will receive continuous visual feedback on both your compression depth and rate on the screen of your phone.

title: Step 1/8. Open TCPR Link app
displayTitle: Step 1/8. Open TCPR Link app
body: In case of a nearby suspected cardiac arrest, you will receive an alert in your myResponder app and accept to run to the scene and confirm arrival.  Upon arrival you need to open the TCPR Link app and press "995" to establish communication with the dispatcher at 995.

title: component
body:
• How TCPR Link works and can be used to improve the collaboration between CPR volunteers and dispatcher to increase the odds of surviving from a cardiac arrest.
     
  • How to set up and use TCPR Link together with CPR Card, enabling you to perform good CPR in collaboration with a dispatcher.

title: Open the TCPR Link app
displayTitle: Open the TCPR Link app
body: Remember to open TCPR Link app when you arrive at the scene.

title: Turn on CPR card
displayTitle: Turn on CPR card
body: Turn on CPR card by pinching the card for a while when you arrive at the scene

title: Do CPR
displayTitle: Do CPR
body: Remember to place the CPRcard on the patient's chest and place the phone beside the patient. Follow the dispatcher's instructions. He or she will help you with this.

title: Step 4/8. Card placement
displayTitle: Step 4/8. Card placement
body: Remove the liner on the backside and place the card in the center of the patient's chest. The glue will make the card stay in place during CPR.

title: Step 6/8. Communicate with the 995
displayTitle: Step 6/8. Communicate with the 995
body: The dispatcher will be able see you and talk to you via the TCPR Link app. Follow the instructions and prepare to start CPR.

title: Step 8/8. The dispatcher's role
displayTitle: Step 8/8. The dispatcher's role
body: The app streams CPR data and video to the dispatcher, who uses this to coach you to perform good CPR. Follow the instructions and get help from a bystander to place the phone in a good position to see the patient.

title: Too deep and too slow
displayTitle: Too deep and too slow
body:
If the compressions are too deep, the lower rectangle in the depth indicator of the CPRcard (upper left) will turn yellow. On the TCPR Link app, the lower part of the depth indicator bar (left side) will turn orange. Release pressure to achieve your depth target.

If the compression rate is too slow, the left light on the rate indicator of CPRcard and TCPR Link app turns yellow.

title: Step 2/8. Remove clothes to bare the chest
displayTitle: Step 2/8. Remove clothes to bare the chest
body:
When you reach the patient, remove clothes to bare the chest. 

The CPR card should be placed on the patient's bare skin, to allow the adhesive backing on the CPRcard to stick to the skin

title: Correct depth and rate
displayTitle: Correct depth and rate
body:
The green light in the rate indicator lights up when a rate of 100 - 120 compressions per minute is reached.

 A steady green light will light up when you reach the compression depth target of 4-6 cm, on a firm surface.

title: Too shallow and too fast
displayTitle: Too shallow and too fast
body:
If the compressions are too shallow, the upper rectangle in the depth indicator of the CPRcard (upper left) will turn yellow. On the TCPR Link app, the upper part of the depth indicator bar (left side) will turn orange. Press deeper to achieve your depth target.

If the compression rate is too fast, the right light on the rate indicator of CPRcard and TCPR Link app turns yellow.

title: How to use CPRcard
displayTitle: How to use CPRcard
body:
Study the user manual you received together with CPRcard before using the device.

Turn the CPRcard on by pinching and holding the On/Off button. Two yellow lights will start flashing indicating that the device is on and ready for use. 

Take off the protective liner on the back of the card only when using the CPRcard on a patient. Place the card in the center of the chest as illustrated on the card (red  placement line) . The feedback panel shall face towards the head of the patient. If needed, wipe fluids off the chest.                                                                                                                                               

Do not remove the liner if you only practice CPR with CPRcard on a manikin.                                                                                                                                                        

Use standard CPR hand placement technique. When the hands are placed correctly on the CPRcard, the feedback panel should be visible.

title: Laerdal text
body:
The TCPR Link app has a functionality called “Test CPR feedback”, available under settings (cogwheel in upper right corner). This functionality can be used to become familiar with the realtime feedback you will receive in the app and no data will be streamed during use of this functionality. 

Open TCPR and open settings and press “Try CPR feedback”. The following screens should appear in your app:

_items.title: Start CPR test
_items.body: Tap on «Test CPR feedback» under Settings, to start

_items.title: No streaming message
_items.body: No data will be streamed 995 during CPR feedback test.  Click "ok" to continue.

_items.title: Turn on CPRcard
_items.body: Turn on you card and start CPR

_items.title: Try CPR
_items.body: Try CPR on a pillow and use the feedback

body: Please confirm that you did a practice session in TCPR Link app before proceeding.

_items.text: I completed a practice session in TCPR Link app

Thank you for completing a practice session in TCPR Link app.

Please continue to the next page.
